 structures and institutions, seeking patterns within the city’s riot of people, events, and influences. As sociologist Robert J. Sampson notes in his new foreword, though much has changed since The City was first published, we can still benefit from its charge to explain where and why individuals and social groups live as they do.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSociology, Urban. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBurgess, Ernest W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBurgess, Ernest W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMckenzie, R. D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark, Robert E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSampson, Robert J.1 aSampson, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWirth, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226636641423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226636641.jpg  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles